content:
✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: Well-thought out and a challenge stepped up from the Medium level puzzle.

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: Nice one!
What is the "write-up" you are referring to? Do you mean the comments in the contribution view? If so, I think suggesting to solve the other puzzle first is sufficient.

No, I was mostly referring to the other puzzle's visual display of cages.   I have updated the goal per your recommendation.  I'll evaluate further when we see feedback from users that may not be familiar with Killer Sudoku and may have chosen not to look at the original puzzle.
I appreciate you taking a look!
Thank you, I'm glad you liked it!

I just cut all my times by 33%. I wish I could increase the number of puzzles, but to go over 42 or so, I would have to change my input format again and it would just get too cryptic for my tastes.

I'm planning on exploring more Extreme Challenges for the other grid type problems. I am kind of fascinated by the candidate reduction techniques that come to mind if you stare at these grids long enough.

Also in general, it is not a good idea to revise a puzzle after approval except for necessary corrections, especially when quite a few people have solved the unedited version already.

You may try the Codewars puzzle I told you about in the forum PM, and maybe you can write a similar puzzle here. Maybe it'll become a puzzle with a viewer and not in text, in order to cope with multiple possible solutions.

That looks good.

I've just found that some input lines (23 to be exact if my count is correct) contain trailing spaces, e.g. there is one in the 8 Puzzles Test. Please remove all of the trailing spaces. Thanks.
I got the same count as you.  23 trailing spaces removed.  Great catch, thank you!

Wow. This is a real challenge. In some cases, it can take over 1 second to solve just 1 of the dozens of puzzles contained in a test case, if I use my code for Killer Sudoku Solver, after slight modifications to adapt to the revised input format here. (And 5 to 6 seconds in a few puzzles. All the times quoted are offline records, not on CG IDE.)

I've rewritten around 90% of the old code, and also copied some ideas from Kakuro Solver. Now I'm able to pass all the tests and validators. And I'm still using Algorithm X. It just shows how unoptimised my old code is :)

I am thrilled to hear this. In the original puzzle, I was not able to solve the last test case using Algorithm X without timing out.  That lead me down the optimization rabbit hole and I was eventually able to eliminate all backtracking.  This is definitely a challenging puzzle and I I feel even better about it now knowing we have two different valid solutions, one with backtracking and one without.
